<paper id="1577437452"><title>Analysis of Timed Systems Based on Time-Abstracting Bisimulation</title><year>1996</year><authors><author org="Miniparc-Zirst" id="80538963">Stavros Tripakis</author><author org="Miniparc-Zirst" id="2096597339">Sergio Yovine</author></authors><n_citation>47</n_citation><doc_type>Conference</doc_type><references><reference>1499481996</reference><reference>1552249698</reference><reference>1574289075</reference><reference>1595519602</reference><reference>1599105192</reference><reference>1874725288</reference><reference>1903000972</reference><reference>1967761514</reference><reference>2016079448</reference><reference>2071152819</reference><reference>2101508170</reference><reference>2118956464</reference><reference>2121539168</reference><reference>2124563781</reference><reference>2137865376</reference><reference>2176837466</reference></references><venue id="1162450063" type="C">Computer Aided Verification</venue><doi>10.1007/3-540-61474-5_72</doi><keywords><keyword weight="0.54696">Transition system</keyword><keyword weight="0.43682">Abstraction</keyword><keyword weight="0.51261">Modulo</keyword><keyword weight="0.437">Computer science</keyword><keyword weight="0.44878">Algorithm</keyword><keyword weight="0.53122">Minimal model</keyword><keyword weight="0.45772">Theoretical computer science</keyword><keyword weight="0.68602">Timed automaton</keyword><keyword weight="0.61412">Bisimulation</keyword><keyword weight="0.63105">Hybrid automaton</keyword></keywords><publisher>Springer, Berlin, Heidelberg</publisher><abstract>We adapt a generic minimal model generation algorithm to compute the coarsest finite model of the underlying infinite transition system of a timed automaton. This model is minimal modulo a time-abstracting bisimulation. Our algorithm uses a refinement method that avoids set complementation, and is considerably more efficient than previous ones. We use the constructed minimal model for verification purposes by defining abstraction criteria that allow to further reduce the model and to compare it to a specification.</abstract></paper>